<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-cleanup-standard-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">The standard cleanup tier, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A standard cleanup is the middle of three cleanup tiers. You&rsquo;re here when more than one thing is wrong <em>and</em> the books are several months &mdash; up to roughly a year &mdash; behind: a few months unreconciled <em>plus</em> miscategorized transactions <em>plus</em> a chart of accounts that&rsquo;s grown messy; or a bank-feed mess that left duplicates and an off reconciliation in its wake; or a year of history that landed scrambled after a migration. It&rsquo;s more than a single contained fix, but it isn&rsquo;t a multi-year, multi-entity, or structurally broken file.</p>
      <p>The work is straightforward in shape and fixed in price: reconcile every bank, credit-card, and loan account to its statements; clean up the categorization and the chart of accounts; remove duplicates and recover gaps; and catch the backlog up to the present period &mdash; then hand the file off CPA-ready. A standard cleanup is typically a <strong>$3,000&ndash;$7,500</strong> fixed fee, scoped in writing after a free file review. Where a single, contained issue is the <a href="/quickbooks/cleanup/focused/">focused tier</a> ($1,200&ndash;$3,000) and a multi-year or structural mess is the <a href="/quickbooks/cleanup/complex/">complex tier</a> ($7,500&ndash;$15,000+), standard is the cluster-of-issues middle ground. We do the cleanup; your CPA files the return &mdash; we don&rsquo;t file taxes, and we&rsquo;re not Intuit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

